%N A003499 a(n) = 6*a(n-1) - a(n-2), with a(0) = 2, a(1) = 6.
%C A003499 Two times Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind evaluated at 3.
%C A003499 Also 2(a(2*n)-2) and a(2*n+1)-2 are perfect squares. - Mario Catalani (mario.catalani(AT)unito.it), Mar 31 2003
%C A003499 Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind evaluated at 3, then multiplied by 2. - _Michael Somos_, Apr 07 2003
%C A003499 Also gives solutions > 2 to the equation x^2 - 3 = floor(x*r*floor(x/r)) where r=sqrt(2). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Feb 14 2004
%C A003499 Output of Lu and Wu's formula for the number of perfect matchings of an m X n Klein bottle where m and n are both even specializes to this sequence for m=2. - _Sarah-Marie Belcastro_, Jul 04 2009
%C A003499 It appears that for prime P = 8*n +- 3, that a((P-1)/2) == -6 (mod P) and for all composites C = 8*n +- 3, there is at least one i < (C-1)/2 such that a(i) == -6 (mod P). Only a few of the primes P of the form 8*n +-3, e.g., 29, had such an i less than (P-1)/2. As for primes P = 8*n +- 1, it seems that the sum of the two adjacent terms, a((P-1)/2) and a((P+1)/2), is congruent to 8 (mod P). - _Kenneth J Ramsey_, Feb 14 2012 and Mar 05 2012
%C A003499 For n >= 1, a(n) is also the curvature of circles (rounded to the nearest integer) successively inscribed toward angle 90 degree of tangent lines, starting with a unit circle. The expansion factor is 5.828427... or 1/(3 - 2*sqrt(2)), which is also 3 + 2*sqrt(2) or A156035. See illustration in links. - _Kival Ngaokrajang_, Sep 04 2013
%C A003499 Except for the first term, positive values of x (or y) satisfying x^2 - 6*x*y + y^2 + 32 = 0. - _Colin Barker_, Feb 08 2014
