%F A003499 For all sequence elements n, 2*n^2 - 8 is a perfect square. Limit_{n->infinity} a(n)/a(n-1) = 3 + 2*sqrt(2). - _Gregory V. Richardson_, Oct 06 2002
%F A003499 a(2*n)+2 is a perfect square, 2(a(2*n+1)+2) is a perfect square. a(n), a(n-1) and A077445(n), n > 0, satisfy the Diophantine equation x^2 + y^2 - 3*z^2 = -8. - Mario Catalani (mario.catalani(AT)unito.it), Mar 24 2003
%F A003499 a(n+1) is the trace of n-th power of matrix {{6, -1}, {1, 0}}. - _Artur Jasinski_, Apr 22 2008
%F A003499 a(n) = Product_{r=1..n} (4*sin^2((4*r-1)*Pi/(4*n)) + 4). [Lu/Wu] - _Sarah-Marie Belcastro_, Jul 04 2009
%F A003499 a(n) = (1 + sqrt(2))^(2*n) + (1 + sqrt(2))^(-2*n). - _Gerson Washiski Barbosa_, Sep 19 2010
%F A003499 For n > 0, a(n) = A001653(n) + A001653(n+1). - _Charlie Marion_, Dec 27 2011
%F A003499 For n > 0, a(n) = b(4*n)/b(2*n) where b(n) is the Pell sequence, A000129. - _Kenneth J Ramsey_, Feb 14 2012
%F A003499 From _Peter Bala_, Jan 06 2013: (Start)
%F A003499 Let F(x) = Product_{n >= 0} (1 + x^(4*n+1))/(1 + x^(4*n+3)). Let alpha = 3 - 2*sqrt(2). This sequence gives the simple continued fraction expansion of 1 + F(alpha) = 2.16585 37786 96882 80543 ... = 2 + 1/(6 + 1/(34 + 1/(198 + ...))). Cf. A174501.
%F A003499 Also F(-alpha) = 0.83251219269380007634 ... has the continued fraction representation 1 - 1/(6 - 1/(34 - 1/(198 - ...))) and the simple continued fraction expansion 1/(1 + 1/((6-2) + 1/(1 + 1/((34-2) + 1/(1 + 1/((198-2) + 1/(1 + ...))))))). Cf. A174501 and A003500.
%F A003499 F(alpha)*F(-alpha) has the simple continued fraction expansion 1/(1 + 1/((6^2-4) + 1/(1 + 1/((34^2-4) + 1/(1 + 1/((198^2-4) + 1/(1 + ...))))))).
%F A003499 (End)
%F A003499 G.f.: G(0), where G(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x*(8*k-9)/( x*(8*k-1) - 3/G(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 12 2013
%F A003499 Inverse binomial transform of A228568 [Bhadouria]. - _R. J. Mathar_, Nov 10 2013
%F A003499 From _Peter Bala_, Oct 16 2019: (Start)
%F A003499 4*Sum_{n >= 1} 1/(a(n) - 8/a(n)) = 1.
%F A003499 8*Sum_{n >= 1} (-1)^(n+1)/(a(n) + 4/a(n)) = 1.
%F A003499 Series acceleration formulas for sum of reciprocals:
%F A003499 Sum_{n >= 1} 1/a(n) = 1/4 - 8*Sum_{n >= 1} 1/(a(n)*(a(n)^2 - 8)) and
%F A003499 Sum_{n >= 1} (-1)^(n+1)/a(n) = 1/8 + 4*Sum_{n >= 1} (-1)^(n+1)/(a(n)*(a(n)^2 + 4)).
%F A003499 Sum_{n >= 1} 1/a(n) = ( (theta_3(3-2*sqrt(2)))^2 - 1 )/4 and
%F A003499 Sum_{n >= 1} (-1)^(n+1)/a(n) = ( 1 - (theta_3(2*sqrt(2)-3))^2 )/4, where theta_3(x) = 1 + 2*Sum_{n >= 1} x^(n^2) (see A000122). Cf. A153415 and A067902.
%F A003499 (End)
%F A003499 E.g.f.: 2*exp(3*x)*cosh(2*sqrt(2)*x). - _Stefano Spezia_, Oct 18 2019
